            "answer_text": "Like Don Grushkin, I\u2019m also offended by the tone of incredulity and the underlying audism behind OP\u2019s question. In addition to what Don has shared in his answer (all of which are true), I would also add this: It is not only possible, but quite EASY for many Deaf people to live without music. In my case, I was born Deaf. It does not mean I hear \u201cnothing,\u201d or that I don\u2019t know what sounds mean. Far from it. I understand what sounds mean, and that almost everything will produce a sound, and some of them will produce vibrations that can be felt. But what you must understand, OP\u2026vibrations by themselves don\u2019t tell us much. For example, vibrations only let us know that the sound is low-pitched or high-pitched and whether it\u2019s being transmitted continuously or intermittently. That\u2019s it. Nothing else. Vibrations don\u2019t tell us if the sound is pleasurable or annoying. Vibrations don\u2019t tell us if the sound contains words. Vibrations don\u2019t tell us if the quality of sound is top-notch or what. After a while, vibrations by themselves can and do become BORING. Yes. Boring. Boring. Boring. Got that? There\u2019s nothing inherently fascinating or exciting about vibrations. (Vibrators for women, on the other hand\u2026but that\u2019s a different subject.) My ears don\u2019t work well enough to appreciate all the nuances of music. My ears can\u2019t even identify various instruments used in any piece of music, except for drums, which are easily identifiable by feel. Again, drums? How many times can I feel drumbeats before it gets old? Surprisingly short time. It gets old fast, because there\u2019s not really all that much variations between drumbeats in themselves. We don\u2019t really learn anything new or get much out of drumbeats in general. On top of all of that, my ears cannot distinguish voices and words in music (or news or any other audio recording). I will always need captions OR interpreters to know what is being said or sung. The inclusion of a third party means what I am watching is being filtered through whatever the captioner or interpreter does, and it affects my perception. It\u2019s not just me and this piece of music. It\u2019s me, this person, this person, and however how many other people who tell me their assessment of this piece of music. That\u2019s not really ideal. I don\u2019t like not having autonomy. I want to be able to judge something for myself\u2026and I simply cannot do that, with my own ears. So\u2026instead of staying either in denial about what my ears can or cannot do, or trying to pretend to enjoy music to please ignorant hearing people like you, which is the true hell of audism that YOU want me to stay in, in order to please you. I prefer to be honest with myself and eschew music. I get to retain my autonomy. My honesty and my willingess to stand up for myself has freed me from the constant denial and the constant pretending. I don\u2019t want to be in Audism Hell and I refuse to go along with what hearing people want. It\u2019s not worth it. Instead of expecting ME to act like a hearing person, how about recognizing that not everything in life can be shared in exact same way? It does not mean my life sucks. NO. My life is wonderful, thank you. My born-Deaf children would also say the same about their lives. Stop imposing your hearing-centered perceptions on Deaf people. It\u2019s ableist\u2026as well as audist. ",
