            "answer_text": "They don't, clearly all the deafs just curl up and die without music to bring their life meaning and joy and the beautiful Deaf woman beside me is a zombie, oh no! Unlike those of us that hear the Deaf can choose if they want to have anything to do with music of any kind and some do and some don't, personally there are times I think this gives them a huge advantage over us. Don Grushkin already covered visual music better than I could so I'll stick with the kind hearies assume is both the only kind and can only be experienced with the ear holes. My girlfriend is Deaf and there is a decent chance her classical music education surpasses yours dear audist OP, for sure it is greater than mine. Just because they don't experience sounds the same way that we do doesn't mean they are insensate. She can read sheet music and play the piano, things she decided she wanted to learn for fun as a kid. She can hear music with her body by feeling the vibrations and has listened to many instruments being played by touching them and can tell the difference between them. She has corrected people on composition questions on people I didn't even know existed, total music nerd! And it isn't just classical music, my born Deaf unicorn kicked my butt knowing answers to a music trivia game show we watched part of the other night, song lyrics are a form of poetry and she enjoys poetry. Moral of the answer: The Deaf are not sad creatures living pathetic silent existences, they are simply human beings who do not hear. They may or may not care about something you clearly think is a valuable part of your life, personally I find it disturbing when someone makes music that utterly important but you do you. ",
