            "answer_text": "Many many people have asked me and continue to ask me, \u2018Oh, Saras! You cannot listen to music?!!! \u2018, furrowing their brows causing lines deep lines on their foreheads, sympathetically throwing in a I\u2019m sooooo sorry you cannot listen to music look, probably with their favourite saddest background score playing in the back of their heads, to which I respond with nothing but a mere shrug that means \u2018I don\u2019t fucking care about it!\u2019, all the while wondering how can someone even come up with such absurd questions with their half baked brains. A friend of mine who met me to invite to his wedding, even mentioned that the only thing he felt so sorry about me being deaf was that I miss out on music. I really felt sorry for his fiancee. I was hearing once upon a time and although it was a long time ago, I could remember what it was like to listen to a favourite song. Sure it was nice. But I don\u2019t care now. I really don\u2019t. I mean what\u2019s the point, even if I care? So to answer your question, deaf people live without music, just as how some people live, with an utter lack of sensitivity in their minds to not ask ridiculous, inconsiderate, inaccurate and nonsensical questions. While these people can change by becoming a little more compassionate and a lot less stupid, we cannot change ours and some may even choose not to, even if they had a choice. ",
