            "author_info": {
                "name": "Don Grushkin",
                "href": "/profile/Don-Grushkin"
            },
            "answer_text": "This question is quite offensive in its underlying premise, that Deaf people are suffering because we don\u2019t hear music, therefore our lives are joyless and meaningless. Cue the wails, the gnashing of teeth, the lamentations of our misfortune at having been born Deaf, that we cannot experience the joy of sound, the wonders of music! Not so. Yes, it\u2019s true that music is an element of life that brings joy and vibrancy to any culture. But there is nothing that says music has to be an auditory experience. As Deaf people, we experience life visually, and for us, music is a visual experience. Watch the ripples on a lake, and how the reflection changes with the movement \u2014 is this not music?  Or the murmuration of a flock of starlings \u2014 tell me you can\u2019t see the music in this:  Ella Mae Lentz, a well-known Deaf Poet, created a poem expressing this very idea of seeing music in our everyday visual life:  We don\u2019t appreciate music solely as a natural phenomenon \u2014 we create music of our own. There are Deaf cheers/songs with a 1\u20132, 1\u20132\u20133 beat:  And, my personal favorite, from the movie \u201cIn the Land of the Deaf\u201d \u2014 in this one, a whole orchestra explodes in my head every time (in fact, I wish more Deaf would experiment with creating sign-based songs in this vein, instead of doing the whole humdrum sign-supported music translations of Hearing music):  So, to answer your question, we get along just fine, because we HAVE music \u2014 it just isn\u2019t YOUR kind of music! ",
