        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Israel Ramirez",
                "href": "/profile/Israel-Ramirez"
            },
            "answer_text": "I have a large music collection: LP\u2019s, CD\u2019s, and even mp3\u2019s. I never learned to play and my singing was always dreadful but music was important to me for most of my life. Gradual hearing loss forced me to abandon music collection. I can detect when music is playing but it\u2019s all a smeared out mush. I can\u2019t make out the words in songs. I can\u2019t detect rhythm. I can\u2019t sense melody. I can\u2019t make out harmony. Timbre and texture are completely gone. Singing in church used to be a pleasure. I never cared for the lyrics to most hymns but I enjoyed the opportunity to sing loudly without anyone complaining about how badly I sang. That\u2019s gone. I can\u2019t follow the music any more. Only the preachy and unartistic lyrics remain. Friedrich Nietzsche is supposed to have said that \u201cWithout music, life would be a mistake.\u201d There was a time when I felt that way. But I learned that life is rich. There is so much else out there for me to enjoy. There\u2019s nature, visual arts, using one\u2019s hands, food, composing answers for Quora, books, other people, and most splendid of all, there\u2019s love. Imagine a huge banquet with lots of different foods in front of you. Your physician has recently told you to avoid eating wheat products on account of celiac disease. Do you spend your time moaning about not being able to eat bread or do you enjoy all the other delicious foods in front of you? So Nietzsche was wrong. What he should have said is \u201cWithout an ability to appreciate the world\u2019s gifts, life would be a mistake.\u201d ",
