        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Kellina James",
                "href": "/profile/Kellina-James"
            },
            "answer_text": "The one thing I have learned having gone from what I thought was hearing to mostly deaf is that all sound is subjective. Sound can equate different in someone elses head. I was a ballet dancer for many years. I assumed that how I heard the music was what everyone heard. It never occurred to me that it could sound different to someone else. Then I got bluetooth music streaming (corrected to my hearing loss) hearing aids. I played a song I had previously choreographed dance to- Bohemian Rhapsody. I had never heard all of the song. There was a whole lot of stuff in there I was not aware of. This explained to me why some of the dancers always performed it different from my choreography. But my point is- The song and the choreography still had meaning even though what we heard was different. I danced for years among dancers that likely heard the music \u201ccorrectly\u201d while I did not hear it the same. Other that being off the music sometimes that I didn\u2019t understand, I adapted and fit in quite well. I taught ballet for many years before I even knew that I heard things \u201cdifferently.\u201d So\u2026 I hear music as what I hear and enjoy it that way. I am ok with the fact that what you hear is different. We can still choose to like or dislike a song. I don\u2019t live without music, it is just different for me. And as it should be\u2026 different for everyone. ",
